[normal]My clients have noted the exchange you had with Lord McNally as follows:
[normal]              
[normal]Sir Alan 
[normal]Beith
[normal]:
[normal]… let's be clear what we are talking about:  Those who represent the majority view in the Chief Pleas … and the Barclay brothers and their management, their economic interests on the island who tend to express their dissatisfaction in extremely strident terms or to take court action which led to some of the democratic changes.
[normal]Lord McNally:
[normal]I was almost tempted to bring two guides to you, one is the Sark scribe and the other is the Sark Newsletter.  In the Sark Scribe, Sark is a bucolic land of people, sheep racing and maypole dancing and having tea at the vicarage and the Sark Newsletter, Sark is a fascist 1930s state.
[normal]Let me be clear, and I'll say again as I have said to the Barclay Brothers and their representative, I wish that they would cease publication of the Sark newsletter because I think it impedes getting the kind of empathetic relationships in Sark that would take the Island forward.
[normal]Lord McNally appeared to identify Sir David and Sir Frederick as publishers of the Newsletter.  This is incorrect.  Mr Delaney alone is the editor and publisher of the Newsletter.  He is 
[normal]ultimately
[normal] responsible for its content, not Sir David and Sir Frederick.
[normal]What is clear from Lord McNally's evidence is that nothing has come of the suggestion in the 2010 report that my clients were somehow responsible for Sark's ability to function properly as a democracy.  The problems identified by Lord McNally have nothing whatsoever to do with my clients.  The criticism is of what can be labelled 
[normal]"
[normal]the Sark establishment
[normal]"
[normal].  Those who would take Sark back to 
[normal]feudalism
[normal] and obstruct reform, investment and 
[normal]progress
[normal] generally, even at the expense of future generations.  That, my clients say, is the true scandal of Sark, 
[normal]the 
[normal]capacity 
[normal]of its establishment 
[normal]to damage itself in the stubborn defence of the
[normal]indefensible and the spurning of assistance and opportunities 
[normal]which 
[normal]any right-minded community would leap at.
[normal]Of course, 
[normal]Lord McNally's evidence
[normal] takes as its premise that there is genuine democracy on Sark, but my clients say there is not
[normal], and this is a fundamental part of the problem on Sark and its lack of progress
[normal].
[normal]It is remarkable to have to report that
[normal] even in the second decade of the 21
[normal]st
[normal] century and even under legislation made only as recently as 2008, the following remains the case on Sark:
