[normal]Meanwhile the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] continues to enjoy an index-linked annuity exceeding £30,000 for 
[normal]unspecified
[normal] duties which will, as matters stand, be inherited by his son
[normal] and future generations
[normal].
[normal]It is a mystery to my clients how the British Government can support the role of 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] in Sark.  The idea of such a figurehead in the United Kingdom only has to be considered to be dismissed as absurd.  The 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] has considerably greater powers 
[normal]in relation to Sark 
[normal]than the Queen
[normal] has in relation to the United Kingdom or any part of it
[normal].  He is very far from being a mere constitutional head of state acting on the advice of elected politicians.
[normal]My clients note though that it was the express intention of the MoJ to push forward reforms of the role of the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] at the time of the making of the 2008 Law.  It was a beginning of reform not an end.
[normal]After what were, to any objective onlooker, very deliberate attempts to avoid reforming the 2008 legislation, the dual role of Seneschal and President of Chief Pleas was finally split in 
[normal]early 2013, only for Lt
[normal].
[normal] Col
