[normal]By contrast, i
[normal]t should be as clear as 
[normal]it 
[normal]possibly can be that it is my clients who have championed true democracy on Sark, only to be obstructed and 
[normal]vilified
[normal] by the Sark establishment and the vested interests it represents, something which is only now coming to light and being appreciated fully.  Sark is not governed well and that is the exclusive responsibility of those in positions of influence and power 
[normal]on Sark, and again it is my clients' complaint that those in Chief Pleas not elected by Sark's electorate 
[normal]retain
[normal] considerable influence and power to obstruct progress, namely the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] and the President of Chief Pleas, along with other prominent individuals who openly oppose progress.
[normal]Sark has no clear leadership because of the 2008 legislation
[normal],
[normal] which left the feudal establishment very largely intact
[normal] and an incomplete democracy
[normal].
[normal]  Sark has been left with two conflicting systems of government.
[normal]  An ineffectual committee
[normal]-
[normal]based system of government continued with chairmen who had no additional powers, not even the committee generally recognised to be the most important, the General Purposes and Advisory Committee.  Even the seating arrangements of Chief Pleas continued unchanged, notwithstanding the supposed introduction of democracy, with the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] sitting on a large wooden throne on an elevated dais, flanked by the President on a slightly smaller wooden throne.
[normal]  There is no opposition or opposition party of any political persuasion and no separation of powers between Chief Pleas as a whole, Chief Pleas as a legislature, or as an executive given the confusion of all roles and the committees drawn from it.  Indeed the 2008 Law gets off to a bad start when it expressly provides at s.1 that "all legislative and executive functions which may be exercised within Sark are exercisable by the Chief Pleas ..".
[normal]  Sark's elected politicians enforce the laws they make, which is  not a healthy system of government.
[normal]The 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] even continues to own the Island of Sark itself and, therefore my clients say, 
[normal]its
[normal] very constitution.  It is open to him to surrender the fief and the Island to the Crown and he has threatened to do so in the past when matters have not gone his way.  At the same time land reform is long overdue with a system of land law which is medieval and entirely without justificat
[normal]ion, including the inability to sub-divide Sark tenements (the parcels of land into which Sark was divided by the settlers of 1565) or to mortgage Sark land.
[normal]  The 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] continues to own the foreshore and all of the "common parts" of Sark not expressly in private or other public ownership.
[normal]True democracy and true democratic leadership on Sark has no chance of success while feudal institutions remain intact.  It is the ultimate cause of the inability to give Sark a clean bill of health.
[normal]Apart from 
[normal]Sark's continuing feudal state
[normal], my clients say that
[normal] there is a further and considerable threat to functioning democracy through the ability of a single group of interests to dominate Chief Pleas entirely and then misuse the assembly by using its legislative powers as a weapon against my clients' interests.
[normal]It is a point which has been raised repeatedly before, but Sark is a single constituency.  All voters
[normal] vote for all candidates
[normal] (and the qualification period 
[normal]for the electoral role 
[normal]was very deliberately extended from 1 to 2 years in 2010, which is part of a pattern of the 
[normal]establishment tightening its control over Sark, a recent example has been to redefine what it is to be ordinarily resident on Sark to qualify as a local person as requiring residence for full
[normal]y 
[normal]273 days a year
[normal] for 15 years).  This means that if a single interest group (here the Sark establishment, those opposing change) can organise sufficient votes to secure the last seat to be filled then you have what amounts to a single party state – which is what Sark effectively has and hence the obstruction even to "ideas", which Lord McNally so strikingly identified.
[normal]  It also means that no individual resident can point to any single 
[normal]Conseiller
[normal] and identify that person as "their" 
[normal]Conseiller
[normal].  All 
[normal]Conseillers
[normal] nominally represent all residents, in reality they represent only themselves.  It is very rarely that a 
[normal]Conseiller
[normal] says that he or she has been asked to take up an issue or a point of view on behalf of a resident.
