[normal]Embargoed copy of the Justice Committee Crown Dependencies Report
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I am instructed on behalf of Sir David and Sir Frederick Barclay.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] I write with reference to paragraphs 46 to 49 of the above report under the heading "Sark".
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients are very concerned to see that a number of allegations are made in your report without any right of reply being given to them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Your
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Committee travelled to Sark
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]and met in person with the Sark political authorities but afforded no opportunity to my clients to comment on what was being
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]said against them, which is fundamentally
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]unfair and a breach of natural justice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It is not sufficient that the Committee states that it has not tested the allegations and does not take sides if it nevertheless publishes the allegations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Indeed it gives credence to the allegations through the recommendation it makes that "... any threat to the ability of (democratic government) to operate fairly and robustly has the potential to raise good government issues which might require UK Government intervention".
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients ask you to note the following:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The events of December 2008 were not reported fairly at the time and are 
[normal]misdescribed
[normal] by you in your report.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The businesses were closed for a matter of days, not weeks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] You should note also that the political authorities who complained that the businesses were closed had actively sought election on an anti-Barclay family/anti-Barclay investment platform in circumstances where, without that investment, all such businesses on Sark would have been closed throughout the winter in any event.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Barclay family's investment programme has in fact continued at
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a rate of millions of pounds per annum and has sustained Sark's economy throughout the recession.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It is unfair to present Sir David and Sir Frederick as repeatedly threatening proceedings and Islanders capitulating because of a lack of resources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Sir David and Sir Frederick are entitled to protect their interests and reputation in the same way as anyone else.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Where letters have been written there has been ample justification, nor have such complaints been pursued in the way that they could have been pursued if Sir David and Sir Frederick carried on in the way you imply.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] There have been no Court proceedings in Sark against individuals of the kind you refer to.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] What your report fails to note is the fact that, but for the considerable efforts of Sir David and Sir Frederick Barclay, there would be no democracy on Sark at all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] When they first came to 
[normal]Brecqhou
[normal] in the 1990s Sark was still a feudal society with a feudal government.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It is largely due to the Barclay family that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the right of male primogeniture in the context of inheritance has been abolished;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the 
[normal]Seigneur's
[normal] feudal right to take 1/13th of the purchase price of all real property transactions by way of private taxation has been abolished; and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]there is a nearly fully elected assembly in Sark rather than one
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]dominated by unelected landowners.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Unfortunately there is still no fully elected assembly on Sark because the Reform (Sark) Law 2008 failed to reform the roles of the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] or the Seneschal, the 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] being the feudal overlord of Sark and the Seneschal being both the speaker of the assembly and the island's principal judge.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Both are unelected and unaccountable to the elected 
[normal]Conseillers
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Both have considerable powers in the new assembly.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Seneschal is the 
[normal]Seigneur's
[normal] appointee for life (no retirement age is stated, he can only be removed voluntarily or by the Lieutenant-Governor for cause).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The 
[normal]Seigneur
[normal] can both speak and move legislation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Seneschal controls debate and runs the business of the assembly.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Sir David and Sir Frederick Barclay brought Judicial Review proceedings in the High Court in London challenging the Ministry of Justice/Privy Council decision to recommend the 2008 Law for Royal Assent.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The English Court of Appeal upheld their challenge to the role of the Seneschal as a breach of Article 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The challenge under Article 3 of the First Protocol (right to free elections) went to the Supreme Court and will now go to Strasbourg.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Far from the Ministry of Justice having to keep a watchful or protective eye over the Sark political authorities/establishment it is Sir David and Sir Frederick who have repeatedly appealed to the Ministry over the years to do what they can to ensure that Sark in fact meets its international law obligations to have a system of government which complies with the European Convention on Human Rights.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Your statement of general principle could not be further from the mark when it comes to the experience of my clients when dealing with Sark.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even now, and notwithstanding the UK government's acceptance of the English Court of Appeal decision as to the Article 6 breach
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]of the dual role of the Seneschal, the Sark political authorities are failing to amend the 2008 Law to separate his roles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Sark is, in effect, failing to make reforms which the UK itself accepted as inevitable when the roles of the Lord Chancellor were separated.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Meanwhile I have instructions to write to the Ministry of Justice again asking them to intervene to urge Sark not to make legislation which patently discriminates against Sir David and Sir Frederick by attempting to prevent them from using their own vessel to transport cargo to and from Sark and 
[normal]Brecqhou
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Your section on Sark fails to recognise that a small jurisdiction can itself become dominated by establishment interests, vested interests
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]and other such cliques requiring
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the Ministry of Justice to keep a watching brief.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] That is the case with Sark and I have files of correspondence with the Ministry to support my clients' position.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients ask that if your report is to be published in its present form that this communication is added to it by way of clarification and answer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Yours faithfully
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Gordon Dawes [bold]Partner[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
