[normal]I am instructed on behalf of Sir David and Sir Frederick Barclay and write further to my letter of 29th March, copy attached for your convenience.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients wish to record formally their concern and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]objection to the fact that your Committee visited Sark, met with individuals who have exhibited bitter enmity against the Barclay family and then
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]published their allegations
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]in a Select Committee report to the House of Commons without first giving my clients the opportunity to respond.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The mere fact that the Committee professed not to take sides or adjudicate on the allegations is neither here nor there.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] You have provided a very public and one-sided platform to Barclay family critics in Sark.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients have asked me to point out that until they began their very substantial investment programme on Sark, there was little or no employment 
[normal]on Sark for 7 or 8 months of the year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Barclay investment programme is worth in the region of 4.5 times the Island's annual public revenue/expenditure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It is intended to create a long term, sustainable economy for Sark based upon an integrated tourist industry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] There is, however, a strong establishment clique which is bitterly opposed to any change on Sark at all, and any investment by the Barclay family in particular.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ask me to emphasise that they have no political role
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]on Sark of any kind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] They have no seats in Chief Pleas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] However, they do insist upon transparency and accountability from the elected 
[normal]Conseillers
[normal] and administrators and work hard to promote the kind of standards which you would accept unquestioningly in the functioning of the House of Commons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Again I point out the irony that it is my clients who have consistently lobbied the Ministry of Justice to ensure Sark government reform as opposed to the Sark authorities lobbying the Ministry for protection or anything of the sort.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is unfair to imply, as your statement of general principle does, that my clients have skewed the operation of democratic government.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Quite the contrary is the case.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Without my clients there would be no recognisable democracy on Sark at all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Again as noted already, the real risk in a small jurisdiction such as Sark is of internal cliques.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] I would draw to your attention the fact that there is no constituency system on Sark of any kind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] All 
[normal]Conseillers
[normal] are elected to represent the whole island; which in reality means that no single 
[normal]Conseiller
[normal] identifiably represents any given
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]section of the populace.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] There is no sense at all of a 
[normal]Conseiller
[normal] representing the interests of those whose views he does not share.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] My clients' very strong impression is that they are entirely without representation in Chief Pleas; a body which consistently works against their interests.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My clients do require an explanation for the coverage you have given of Sark and why they were given no opportunity to reply and how that omission can be rectified beyond the rather weak proposals put forward by the Clerk to the Committee.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Yours faithfully
